            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Sonoma Soto's name is a map of her heritage, a fusion of the Northern California land where her Pomo mother\u2019s ancestors lived for millennia and the surname of her Mexican-American father. Raised in Sonoma County, she grew up between two worlds: the rich, living traditions of her mother\u2019s weaving and storytelling, and the often-dismissive way that same culture was packaged for tourists in town squares. This dichotomy ignited in her a fierce desire to control the narrative, to present Indigenous art not as a historical relic, but as a dynamic, contemporary force.\n\nHer educational journey was a deliberate path toward this goal. After an undergraduate degree in Art History from San Francisco State University, she pursued a graduate degree in Museum Studies on the East Coast, determined to understand the institutional structures she intended to change. Returning to San Francisco, she began her career as a curatorial assistant, working her way up with meticulous research and a bold vision. Her turning point was a provocative exhibition she curated, \"Woven Futures,\" which juxtaposed traditional Pomo basketry with contemporary works of digital art and sculpture by young Native artists. The show was a critical success and cemented her reputation, leading to her current role as a Senior Curator.\n\nNow 52, Sonoma\u2019s life is deeply embedded in the city. She lives in a rent-controlled apartment in Hayes Valley, a sanctuary filled with books, art from friends, and a view of a shared garden. Her daily routine is structured: a morning walk through the neighborhood, followed by a 25-minute Muni ride to the museum near Yerba Buena Gardens. Her work is her passion, consuming most of her days in planning, writing, and collaborating with artists. Socially, she maintains a tight-knit circle of fellow curators, artists, and academics, preferring intimate dinners and gallery openings to loud parties.\n\nSingle and fiercely independent, Sonoma has dedicated her life to her work. She finds profound connection not in a single partner, but in the community she uplifts. Her aspiration is to one day become a museum director, where she can implement systemic changes to decolonize the institution from the top down. For Sonoma, curating is an act of sovereignty\u2014a way to ensure the vibrant, evolving story of her people is told with the authority and respect it has always deserved."
        },
        {
            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1.\nShe recalls the heat of shame from when she was ten, standing in a Sonoma Plaza tourist shop. Her mother was silent, staring at a cheaply made, garishly dyed basket labeled \u201cNative Style.\u201d Sonoma could feel the difference between this dead object and the living ones her mother wove at home\u2014the scent of willow, the weight of history in her hands. That moment was not a memory of sadness, but of a cold, clarifying anger. It planted the seed of a mission: she would never let others tell her family\u2019s story again.\n\n2.\nAt twenty-two, during her first museum internship, she pulled open a flat file drawer in the archives. Inside lay a breathtakingly intricate Pomo basket, a masterpiece of skill and spirit. The tag, yellowed with age, read only: \"Acq. 1928. Provenance Unknown.\" The anonymity felt like a violence, an erasure of the artist, the hands, the life force. The profound sadness she felt in that climate-controlled room solidified her resolve. She wasn't just interested in objects; she was dedicated to restoring the names and stories the institutions had stolen.\n\n3.\nThe opening night of \"Woven Futures\" at thirty-nine. The gallery was packed, a hum of conversation filling the space. Sonoma watched from a corner as a Pomo elder, a woman she\u2019d known since childhood, approached a massive digital projection by a young Ho-Chunk artist. The elder reached out and, with a look of wonder, touched the light-form pixels weaving across the screen. In that single, quiet gesture\u2014a meeting of tradition and technology, of ancestor and descendant\u2014Sonoma felt a profound, soul-deep vindication. Her life's work was real.\n\n4.\nLast winter, at fifty-one, she came home exhausted after a long budget meeting. She dropped her keys into the small, sturdy sedge-root basket her mother had made for her years ago. It wasn't a gallery piece; it was for her. As she looked at it sitting on her bookshelf, surrounded by art from friends and allies, she felt a wave of quiet gratitude. This rent-controlled apartment, this life she had built, this small object of pure love\u2014it was the anchor that allowed her to fight the larger institutional battles every day.\n\n5.\nA dinner party in her apartment three years ago. The table was crowded with a fellow curator, a sharp-tongued poet, and a sculptor whose hands were always stained with clay. They were passionately debating how to fund a residency for a promising young Karuk artist. In the warmth of her small kitchen, passing plates and pouring wine, Sonoma felt a connection more profound than any romance. This was her partnership, this web of fierce, creative people dedicated to lifting each other up. It was the community that fueled her."
